                    <abstract lang="eng">We study two-dimensional motion perception in flies using a semicircular visual stimulus. Measurements of both the H1-neuron and the optomotor response are consistent with a simple model supposing spatial integration of the outputs of correlation-type motion detectors. In both experiment and model, there is substantial H1 and horizontal (yaw) optomotor response to purely vertical motion of the stimulus. We conclude that the fly&apos;s optomotor response to a two-dimensional pattern, depending on its structure, may deviate considerably from the direction of pattern motion.</abstract>
